In this paper, we contribute to closing this gap by
assessing and intercomparing the impacts of future climate
change under a set of different socio-economic scenarios in
the catchments of four European lagoons. Lagoons and their
drainage areas are complex ecosystems that are particularly
vulnerable to climate change (Jeffress et al.

The main objective of our study is to provide a scientiﬁc
basis for the development of an integrated water resources
and coastal zone management strategy for European
lagoons in the context of climate change. We analyzed a
wide range of parameters regarding water availability and
nutrients using an eco-hydrological model and a set of 15
climate scenarios in combination with four different socio-
economic scenarios per case study area.
